class Solution {
    public int minChanges(int n, int k) {
        if ((n & k) != k) return -1;
        int changes = 0;
        while (n != k) {
            n &= n - 1;
            changes++;
        }
        return changes;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The approach checks if it's possible to make n equal to k by verifying if k is a subset of n in terms of bit representation. It then counts the number of 1-bits in n that need to be cleared to make n equal to k. This is achieved by iteratively clearing the least significant 1-bit in n until n equals k.

